 A. Dupont's Die Geierwally (1921), Carl Ludwig Achaz-Duisberg's Sprengbagger 1010 (1929), and Phil Jützi's Hunger in Waldenburg (1929) document and create a forum for discussing environmental change. The book then looks at film as a visual archive of and catalyst for infrastructure development, focusing on Metropolis (Fritz Lang, 1927), the mountain films of Arnold Fanck, and the Berlin films Stadt der Millionen (Adolf Trotz, 1925), Berlin: Die Sinfonie der Großstadt (Walter Ruttmann, 1927), and Menschen am Sonntag (1930). Nazi-era and postwar films are also examined. By exploring German film history alongside environmental history and theory, this book provides a case study of the power of film within processes of environmental transformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEcocriticism2DLC. 0aHeimatfilmexHistory2DLC. 0aHuman ecology in motion pictures2DLC. 0aMotion pictureszGermanyxHistory2DLC. 0aPlace (Philosophy) in motion pictures2DLC. 4aGerman Film. 4aGerman History. 4aGerman Literature. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAchaz-Duisberg.  aAdolf Trotz.  aArnold Fanck.  aDie Geierwally.  aE. A. Dupont.  aFritz Lang.  aHeimat films.  aHunger in Waldenburg.  aJützi.  aMenschen am Sonntag.  aSprengbagger 1010.  aStadt der Millionen.  aWalter Ruttmann.  acity symphonies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311142849940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781805431459?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781805431459423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781805431459/original  a978-3-11-142849-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles